Good condition High Standard Sentinel MK II in .357MAG.
These guns were the earliest Dan Wesson revolvers made.
High Standard made them under Dan Wesson's design before the opening of Dan Wesson Firearm's first shop.
The Sentinel also sports Dan Wesson's interchangeable barrel system, able to change barrels with other Dan Wesson revolvers.

Finish is above 90%, with minor wear on the center pin housing (typical of use) and where the recoil shield meets the extractor (typical of High Standard's fitting).
All original with wood grips.
Comes with a Simply Rugged Loaded Pancake holster that holds 6 rounds, beautiful basket weaving.
I've been really gentle with this gun shooting only .38SPL.
I'm not the original owner, but it is evident that this revolver was not shot much, or carried often.

Introduced in 2008, the P30L (for Long), has a slide and barrel that measure approximately a half-inch longer in length. Otherwise the P30L is essentially identical to the P30.

Like the P30, the P30L was designed as a modern police and security pistol and combines optimal function and safety. Ergonomic features include a special grip frame with interchangeable backstraps inserts and lateral plates, allowing the pistol to be individually adapted to any user.

Ambidextrous controls include dual slide releases, magazine release levers, and a serrated decocking button located on the rear of the frame (for applicable variants). A Picatinny rail molded into the front of the frame makes mounting lights, laser aimers, or other accessories easy and convenient. The extractor serves as a loaded chamber indicator providing a reminder of a loaded chamber that can be subtly seen and felt. The standard P30L is a 9 mm Variant 3 (V3) with a conventional double-action/single action trigger mode with a serrated decocking button on the rear of the slide.

This model consists of:

P30LS, Long Slide, (V3) DA/SA, w/safety and ambidextrous decocking button

Up for sale is my Franchi SPAS-12 shotgun. I have shot it multiple times and its a ton of fun


Only five percent (about 1,850) of the estimated SPAS-12 shotguns manufactured were imported into the U.S. The SPAS-12 is a dual-mode shotgun, adjustable for semi-automatic or pump-action operation. The SPAS-12 has been sold to military and police users worldwide, on the civilian market, and has been featured in films and TV shows. The SPAS 12 was designed to function primarily as a semi-automatic firearm, with the pump-action mode used to reliably fire low-pressure ammunition such as tear gas rounds or less-lethal bean bags. The firing mode is switched by pressing a button under the foregrip and sliding the foregrip slightly forwards or backwards until it clicks into position. The SPAS-12 has a magazine cut-off feature, which prevents loading a new round from the internal magazine when the gun is cycled. This allows the operator to load a specialized round into the chamber without firing the entire magazine first. The barrel of the SPAS 12 was externally threaded to accept a variety of attachments, from chokes to gas-grenade launchers. The appearance and intended purpose of the SPAS-12 initially led to its "combat" designation. Franchi renamed the model the Sporting Purpose Automatic Shotgun in 1990, after the importation ban of 1989 (when it was called the Special Purpose Automatic Shotgun). This allowed continued sales to the U.S. as a limited-magazine-capacity, fixed-stock model until 1994. Following the Federal Assault Weapons Ban, exports to the U.S. ceased.
